wrestling isn‚Äôt just for champions. it‚Äôs for anyone willing to show up and work. if we only cater to the elite, we shrink the sport. growth comes from inclusion.

most wrestlers lose matches because of mistakes they make before they even step on the mat‚Äîpoor fueling. this cheat sheet gives you a simple plan for what to eat and drink before, during, and after matches when weigh-ins happen just two hours before.

every season has a purpose: pre-season = build in-season = perform off-season = recover + improve don‚Äôt just train. know what you‚Äôre training for.
whoever said there are no dumb questions has never been in a sports parent group chat.
want to wrestle smarter, not just harder? matclub delivers no-fluff advice to your inbox. subscribe:
wrestling isn‚Äôt about doing more. it‚Äôs about doing the right things, over and over. get no-fluff strategies to train, coach, and parent better. subscribe here:
wrestle less. train smart. move more. off-season is the time to cross-train. add variety to stay fresh and avoid burnout.
try new moves. fix bad habits. attend clinics. off-season is where your skill set expands. no pressure = perfect time to experiment.
the off-season isn‚Äôt just for recovery ‚Äî it‚Äôs for reinvention. heal, reflect, and rebuild. what didn‚Äôt work? what needs to level up?
practice doesn‚Äôt make perfect. perfect reps, full focus, and clear goals do. treat every drilling session like it actually matters ‚Äî because it does.
want to improve faster? start journaling after practice. log what you drilled, what felt off, and what you‚Äôre working on next. it‚Äôll compound.
most wrestlers go on autopilot halfway through practice. the best ones? they stay locked in from warm-up to cool-down.
before you hit that shot in practice ‚Äî close your eyes. visualize it first. the brain doesn‚Äôt know the difference between mental reps and real ones. use that to your advantage.
if your drill partner isn‚Äôt pushing you, they‚Äôre holding you back. find someone who makes you uncomfortable. then keep drilling until it becomes comfortable.
wrestling is a game of inches. hand placement. foot angles. head position. focus on the small details ‚Äî they‚Äôre what win close matches.
‚Äúactive rest‚Äù is a cheat code during practice. instead of standing still, stay loose, stretch, breathe, or shadow drill. your body (and coach) will thank you later.
do 10 perfect reps. not 20 lazy ones. quality > quantity ‚Äî especially in drilling.
what‚Äôs the most overrated part of a typical #wrestling practice? and what‚Äôs underrated?
if you walk into practice without a goal, don‚Äôt be surprised when you leave without progress. set one focus. write it down. then drill like it matters.
